{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493378","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493378"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:08:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:08:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1303"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1303","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1303"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.78,0.04,0.02,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1303"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54678"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1303","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1303"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1303"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40205"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"128"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1054"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1060"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1542"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42280"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54678","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54678"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of chest pain and mild shortness of breath. The chest pain worsens on deep inspiration and lying flat. It does not radiate to her arm or jaw. She reports having an upper respiratory tract infection for the past week. Her medical history includes a deep vein thrombosis five years ago, treated with apixaban. She does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears mildly unwell. Her pulse rate is 104/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.0\u00b0C. Cardiovascular examination reveals a pericardial friction rub. The remainder of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following findings would most strongly support the likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Positive group A streptococcal throat swab","Diffuse ST elevation with concave upward morphology on electrocardiogram","Patchy opacities on chest X-ray","Pain reproduced on rib palpation","Filling defect in pulmonary arteries on computed tomography pulmonary angiography"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is highly suggestive of acute pericarditis. The clinical triad of chest pain worsened by inspiration and lying flat, fever, and a pericardial friction rub strongly supports this diagnosis. Acute pericarditis often occurs following a viral upper respiratory tract infection, as in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiffuse ST elevation with concave upward morphology on electrocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E is the characteristic ECG finding in acute pericarditis. This ECG change is seen in up to 90% of cases and is present in all leads except aVR and V1. The ST elevation in pericarditis is typically concave upward (saddle-shaped) and not localized to a specific coronary artery distribution, distinguishing it from ST-elevation myocardial infarction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epositive group A streptococcal throat swab\u003C/strong\u003E would support a diagnosis of streptococcal pharyngitis or potentially rheumatic fever. However, rheumatic fever is less likely in this case as the patient lacks other major Jones criteria, and the presentation is more consistent with viral pericarditis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPatchy opacities on chest X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E are typically seen in pneumonia. While pneumonia can cause chest pain and fever, it would not explain the pericardial friction rub or the positional nature of the chest pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPain reproduced on rib palpation\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of costochondritis. While costochondritis can occur following a viral infection and cause chest pain, it would not account for the fever, pericardial friction rub, or the pain worsening when lying flat.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Efilling defect in pulmonary arteries on computed tomography pulmonary angiography\u003C/strong\u003E would indicate a pulmonary embolism (PE). While PE is a consideration given the patient\u0027s history of deep vein thrombosis, the presence of a pericardial friction rub and the characteristic chest pain of pericarditis make PE less likely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn conclusion, while all the options presented could potentially cause chest pain, the clinical presentation and examination findings in this case are most consistent with acute pericarditis. The diffuse ST elevation with concave upward morphology on ECG would provide the strongest support for this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Viral pericarditis should be considered in young patients presenting with chest pain following a recent respiratory tract infection.","Diffuse ST elevation with concave upward morphology on ECG is characteristic of acute pericarditis.","The clinical triad of chest pain worsened by inspiration and lying flat, fever, and a pericardial friction rub strongly suggests acute pericarditis."],"references":["Imazio M, Gaita F, LeWinter M. Evaluation and Treatment of Pericarditis: A Systematic Review. JAMA. 2015;314(14):1498\u20131506. Available at: https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jama/article-abstract/2456172","Burns, E. Pericarditis. In: Life in the fast lane [online]. 2020 Nov 3 [Cited 2021 Jan 4]. Available at: https://litfl.com/pericarditis-ecg-library/."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40205"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1303"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40205","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40205"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-09T10:46:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-09T10:47:49+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1303"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54678"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"upda